bush vowed to remove iraqi armed forces by various means
( agence france - presse , washington , 14 th ) - u . s . president bush vowed today to lift the armed forces of iraqi president saddam hussein 's regime by " various means . "
he accused : " hussein possesses weapons of mass destruction and used them . he is used to deceive the world and continues to do so . "
hussein has also established ties with the terrorist network . "
in his speech at the us federal bureau of investigation headquarters , bush explained the various efforts made to prevent the terrorist attacks similar to the september 11 , 2001 terrorist attacks . he sternly said : " hussein is a dangerous element , which is the reason why he will be removed from the armed forces by various means . "
this is bush 's first public response to the un security council meeting held in new york today .
the main purpose of the meeting was to hear a report on whether iraq would abide by the resolution 1441 passed by the un security council on november 8 last year .
white house spokesman fleischer said that blix did not provide any reason for people to believe that iraq is observing un security council resolution 1441 .
he told reporters : " the world has not received any news from new york today . it is believed that hussein has shown to the weapons inspectors that he is now disarming . "
the situation is just the opposite . "
asked when the united states will put forward a follow - up resolution aimed at implementing the un security council resolution 1441 , fleischer said , " it is too early to say , " but the united states will consult its allies on the contents of the wording .
for example , france , russia , china , and other countries still advocate strengthening arms inspection against iraq , and do not want the united states to lead a war against iraq .
fleischer said that president bush also thinks military action is the " last resort . "
however , he insisted on the timetable set by bush , saying that the united nations can only try to promote the peaceful liberation of the armed forces in iraq in " a few weeks rather than a few months " and then take military action .
white house to study sanctions against north korea : new york times
( afp report from washington d . c . ) the new york times today quoted a us official as saying that the white house is studying sanctions against pyongyang once it fails to abandon its nuclear weapons development action .
the sanctions will include stopping north korea 's arms delivery and cutting off the remittance of korean people living in japan to north korea , the report said .
the report pointed out that officials of the pentagon and the state department are working out a detailed plan for sanctions to enable the united states to respond at any time when north korea takes new measures to develop nuclear weapons .
according to the new york times , the first step will be to urge the un security council to condemn the recent measures taken by north korea , including the withdrawal from the nuclear non - proliferation treaty and the re - opening of the closed - door nuclear facilities that can be used for the production of weapons , which may be in the next two weeks .
however , washington 's pacific allies are still opposed to the idea of sanctions against north korea , and the un security council may still focus on the iraq issue in the next few weeks .
