us defense department canceled two missile interception tests
xinhua news agency report of january 8 th from washington ( by staff reporter tan xinmu ) - us defense department 's missile defense agency spokesman aznar announced on the 8 th that the us military has decided to cancel the two missile interception tests scheduled for the first half of this year , because the development of a new type of missile for launching the interceptor missile is lagging behind the original process .
aznar told the press here that the missile defense agency needs to concentrate its energy on solving the problem of helping push rockets this year , and the next missile interception test will be carried out after the boeing company produces a new type of rocket this autumn .
the boeing company originally planned to start a flight test of a new type of " interceptor " missile in 2000 , but the test was postponed due to technical reasons .
after the failure of the launch of the rocket in december 2001 , the boeing company decided to re - design the rocket and is scheduled to complete it this autumn .
in the eight land - based missile interception tests that have already been conducted , the us military used the modified " militia " rocket as a substitute boosters , but the test results of this type of boosters are not ideal .
both the missile interception tests conducted in july 2000 and december last year failed because the " interceptor " failed to separate from the rocket .
on 17 december last year , us president bush ordered the defense department to start deploying the missile defense system and strive to build a preliminary missile defense system by september 2004 .
however , many experts believe that in terms of technology alone , the time is not ripe for deploying the missile defense system .
kadish , director of the missile defense agency , also said that the deployment of the entire missile defense system would be affected if the boeing company could not produce up - to - standard rocket as scheduled .
